Process model

\begin{align*} \large{\dfrac{\textrm{d}T(t)}{\textrm{d}t}}&=\large{- k \left(T(t) - T_a\right),} \notag \\ \large{T(t)} &\large{= \left(T(0) - T_{a} \right)\textrm{e}^{-kt} + T_{a}.} \end{align*}

For simplicity, let's assume that $T(0)$ is known (e.g. measurable)

\begin{equation*} \large{\theta = (T_{a},k)^\mathsf{T}}. \end{equation*}

Structural identifiability - perfect data¶

Many software packages include DAISY, GenSSI, STRIKE-GOLDD¶

Practical identifiability - imperfect data¶

Many approaches (e.g. local likelihood-based analysis, global likelihood-based analysis)¶

Noise (measurement) model: Additive Gaussian

\begin{equation*} \large{T^{o}(t) \mid \theta = \mathcal{N}\left(T(t), \sigma^2\right).} \end{equation*}

Series of $I$ measurements leads to log-likelihood function

\begin{equation*} \large{\ell(\theta \mid T^{o}(t)) = \sum_{i=1}^{I} \log \left [\phi\left(T^{o}(t_i); T(t_i), \sigma^2 \right)\right],} \end{equation*}

where $\phi(x; \mu, \sigma^2)$ denotes the probability density function of the normal distribution with mean $\mu$, variance $\sigma^2$.

Maximise the log-likelihood function

\begin{equation*} \large{\sup_{\theta} \ell(\theta \mid T^{o}(t)) \Rightarrow \hat{\theta}.} \end{equation*}

Allows us to work with normalised log-likelihood

\begin{equation*} \large{\bar{\ell}(\theta \mid T^{o}(t)) = \ell(\theta \mid T^{o}(t)) - \ell(\hat{\theta} \mid T^{o}(t)).} \end{equation*}

\begin{equation*} \large{\bar{\ell} \ge \bar{\ell}^{*} = -\dfrac{\Delta_{n,q}}{2},} \end{equation*}

where $\Delta_{n,q}$ $q$th quantile of a $\chi^2$ distribution with $n$ degrees of freedom. Here the 95$\%$ confidence interval $\bar{\ell}^{*} = -\Delta_{2,0.95}/2 \approx -2.9957$.

Prediction: Two approaches¶

1. Grid up the log-likelihood function,¶

2. Rejection sampling of the log-likelihood function to generate M samples,¶

\begin{equation*} \large{\bar{\ell}(\theta \mid T^{o}(t)) \ge \bar{\ell}^*.} \end{equation*}
